</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">This transformation enables the model to interpret the categorical data accurately, leading to better performance in predicting player rankings based on various in-game statistics.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Benefits:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><em><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Improved Model Performance:</span></span></em><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;One-hot encoding ensures that the model can utilize categorical data effectively.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><em><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Avoids Misinterpretation:&nbsp;</span></span></em><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Prevents the model from misinterpreting categorical values as ordinal, which could otherwise lead to incorrect assumptions.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: center;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;"><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="color: transparent; border: none;"></span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 16pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">8.2 Scaling the data:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 16pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Scaling is a preprocessing step in machine learning that adjusts the range of the data features to ensure that they have a comparable scale. This is important because many machine learning algorithms perform better when numerical features are on a similar scale. If features are not scaled, those with larger ranges can dominate the learning process, leading to suboptimal models.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Types of Scaling:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: disc;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Min-Max Scaling (Normalization)</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Scales the data to a fixed range, typically 0 to 1.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Best for algorithms that do not assume any distribution of the data (e.g., k-nearest neighbors, neural networks).</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: disc;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Standard Scaling (Z-score Normalization)</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Scales the data so that it has a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Best for algorithms that assume normally distributed data (e.g., linear regression, logistic regression).</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: disc;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Robust Scaling</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Scales the data using statistics that are robust to outliers (median and interquartile range).</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Useful when data contains outliers.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: disc;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">MaxAbs</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;Scaling</span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Scales the data to the range [-1, 1] by dividing by the maximum absolute value.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: circle;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Useful for sparse data were preserving zero entries is important.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">I have followed standard scaling (Z-score normaliztion) to replace some&nbsp;</span><span style="color: transparent;">attributes like&nbsp;</span><span style="color: transparent;">killPlace</span><span style="color: transparent;">,&nbsp;</span><span style="color: transparent;">killPoints</span><span style="color: transparent;">, and more have shown some high values compared to the rest of the data.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: center;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;"><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="color: transparent; border: none;"></span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">I&nbsp;</span><span style="color: transparent;">have applied the formulae,</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 15pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">(X</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">i</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 15pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">-</span><span style="color: transparent;">X</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">mean</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 15pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">)/</span><span style="color: transparent;">X</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">std</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 16pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">8.3&nbsp;</span><span style="color: transparent;">Splitting</span><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;the data</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 16pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">Splitting the data is a crucial step in preparing a dataset for machine learning modeling. It involves dividing the data into distinct subsets to ensure that the model can be trained and evaluated properly. The most common splits are the training set and the test set, and sometimes a validation set is used as well.</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">How should we s</span><span style="color: transparent;">plit the&nbsp;</span><span style="color: transparent;">d</span><span style="color: transparent;">ata?</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">Training Set:</span></sub></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;This subset of data is used to train the machine learning model. The model learns the relationships between the input features and the target variable from this data.</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">Test Set:</span></sub></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;This subset is used to evaluate the performance of the trained model. It provides an unbiased assessment of how well the model generalizes to new, unseen data.</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">We</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;have a single dataset to both train and test. Hence,&nbsp;</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">I</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;had&nbsp;</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">to&nbsp;</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">split it into two with</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">X</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">input</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">_</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">output</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Y</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;"><sub><span style="color: transparent;">input</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">-output&nbsp;</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">parameters</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;(I</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">nput</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;=&nbsp;</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">T</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">rain,&nbsp;</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">O</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">utput =&nbsp;</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">T</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">est</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">)</span></sub><sub><span style="color: transparent;">.</span></sub></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 9.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>

<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">CatBoost (Categorical Boosting) is a powerful gradient boosting algorithm developed by Yandex. It is designed to handle categorical features efficiently, making it particularly useful for datasets with a mix of numerical and categorical data. CatBoost builds an ensemble of decision trees in a sequential manner, where each tree aims to correct the errors of the previous ones.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>

<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Model Prediction and Evaluation are crucial steps in understanding how well your machine learning model performs on unseen data. In the PUBG game ranking prediction project, after training the CatBoost model, the performance was evaluated using the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) and the R&sup2; score.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Implementation Details:</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 13.5pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: disc;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Making Prdictions:&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">The trained CatBoost model is used to make predictions on the test dataset.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <ul style="list-style-type: disc;color: transparent;">
        <li style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">
            <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Evaluating the Model:</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;The model&apos;s performance is evaluated using RMSE and R&sup2; score.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;RMSE is calculated to measure the average magnitude of the prediction errors. A lower RMSE indicates better model performance.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
<div style="text-align: start;color: transparent;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 12px;">
    <p style="text-align: left;color: transparent;"><strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">R&sup2; Score:</span></span></strong><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;"><span style="color: transparent;">&nbsp;The R&sup2; score is computed to determine the proportion of variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variables. An R&sup2; score close to 1 indicates a high level of accuracy.</span></span><span style="color: transparent;font-size: 12pt;">&nbsp;</span></p>
</div>
